comment.body:
Not at all. It's not an enforcement. The radial menu is a Screen, like the options and such. Minecraft disables movement while interacting with screens by default. In newer versions I have additional logic in the screen that allows it to still process movement controls, bypassing the "pause" (lack of processing) that the game applies on the movement.

The screen opens when you press the keybind, and closes when you release or click. It's all in the client except the actual swapping operation. There should be no server-related delay involved in the animations.

issue.body:
# D365 Migration: Health Check (PCF + Dataverse + Power Automate) ## Summary This PR implements a complete migration of the Salesforce EDA Health Check LWC component to Microsoft Dynamics 365, providing a Dynamics-native solution using PCF controls, Dataverse tables, and Power Automate flows. **Key Components:** - **PCF Control**: TypeScript-based custom control that replicates the LWC UI and behavior - **Dataverse Schema**: Custom tables with `new_` prefix for definitions, groups, items, runs, and settings - **Power Automate Integration**: Flow specifications for backend orchestration (GetHealthCheckViewModel, UpdateHealthCheckLastRunDate) - **Solution Packaging**: Complete deployment and build documentation **Architecture**: The PCF control calls Power Automate flows (or optionally Dataverse custom actions) to fetch health check data and update run dates, maintaining the same user experience as the original Salesforce LWC while leveraging native D365 capabilities. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human **â ï¸ Critical Items (5):** - [ ] **PCF builds successfully** - Run `yarn install && yarn build` in `d365/health-check/pcf/HealthCheckPcf/` to verify TypeScript compilation - [ ] **Flow implementation matches contract** - Implement flows per `docs/FLOWS.md` and verify JSON output exactly matches `ViewModelPayload` interface in `index.ts` - [ ] **Dataverse schema deployment** - Create tables/columns per `schema/README.md` with `new_` prefix and verify relationships work - [ ] **End-to-end testing** - Deploy PCF to model-driven form, configure flow URLs, test: initial load â run button â settings navigation - [ ] **Address CI deprecation warnings** - Update `.github/workflows/*.yml` to use `actions/cache@v3` or `v4` instead of deprecated `v2` **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Set up Dataverse environment with publisher prefix `new_` 2. Create tables and seed data from `schema/seed/healthcheck_seed.json` 3. Implement Power Automate flows A & B per specifications 4. # feat(cli): add --link flag to link configs without installs (issue #29) ## Summary This PR implements a new `--link` CLI flag that enables "link-only" operations as requested in issue #29. When used, the flag creates or updates symlinks for configuration files without running install commands, exporting/importing defaults, or persisting state changes. **Key Features:** - **Link-only execution**: Only processes `link` sections from components, skipping `install` commands - **Postlink hook support**: Runs postlink hooks when present and linking succeeds - **Profile & fuzzy search support**: Works with the same profile selection and fuzzy search as regular runs - **No state persistence**: Intentionally bypasses profile saving and component state updates - **Progress & verbose modes**: Supports both `--verbose` and quiet (progress) execution modes **Files Changed:** - `cmd/dot/main.go`: Added CLI flag, execution path, and state persistence guard - `internal/component/component.go`: Added `LinkComponents` and `LinkComponentsWithProgress` methods - `cmd/dot/main_test.go` & `internal/component/component_test.go`: Added test coverage - `README.md`: Updated with usage examples and behavior description ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **End-to-end testing**: Run `dot --link`, `dot --link [profile]`, and `dot --link [fuzzy]` to verify basic functionality works as expected - [ ] **State isolation**: Verify that link-only operations don't modify `~/.dot/state.json` or persist profile changes (key behavioral difference) - [ ] **Postlink hook execution**: Test components with postlink hooks to ensure they run correctly and handle failures appropriately - [ ] **Error handling**: Test edge cases like components with no links, missing files, permission errors, and failed postlink hooks - [ ] **CLI integration**: Verify the flag works correctly with other flags like `--dry-run`, `--verbose`, and doesn't conflict with existing operations **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. issue.title: [Feedback] Network Console will be removed in Edge 143
issue.body:
Starting with Edge 143, the Network Console tool will be removed from Edge DevTools with no replacement. As our team shifts focus toward delivering more stable features and improving alignment with Chrome, we no longer have the capacity to maintain this tool. We recommend using the REST Client extension for VS Code for API development and testing.

If this feature is important to your workflow, we encourage you to share your feedback. Strong interest could help motivate bringing it to Chromium in the future.

comment.body:
I'll be blunt: this is a baffling and profoundly out-of-touch decision.
To suggest a VS Code extension as a replacement for the Network Console is to fundamentally misunderstand the tool's purpose and our workflow. It's not just a "recommendation," it's a dismissal of the very context-sensitive, in-the-moment debugging that made the tool essential.
Let's call this what it is:
It's a regression, not an improvement. You are actively making your browser a worse tool for developers. The argument about "shifting focus to stable features" is a hollow excuse for removing a feature that was not only stable but was a key differentiator.
It's a surrender of innovation. You had a feature that made developers seriously consider, and even choose, Edge over Chrome. It was a tangible advantage. Now, you are voluntarily throwing that advantage away to become a less-capable clone. Why would we choose a browser that actively removes its best features?
It demonstrates a disconnect from your users. This decision feels like it was made in a vacuum by people who don't actually use the DevTools for complex, day-to-day debugging. If you did, you would know that breaking the browser-context loop is a dealbreaker.
This isn't about "strong interest." We are telling you now: you are removing a critical piece of our toolkit and making our jobs harder for what appears to be your own convenience.
This is how you lose the goodwill of the developer community you've worked so hard to win back. Reverse this decision.
